<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-609-444  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 609 444.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Design  June 18 1990 v18 n12 p31(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Concurrent engineering defines design environment of the future.andO;(part of a special section, the DAC Buying Guide)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Kalekos, Thanasis.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Concurrent design engineering offers a number of benefits,including improved quality, lower costs, and shorter design-cycletimes.andP;  The move toward concurrent engineering is being drivenboth by major corporation such as Allen-Bradley, a manufacturer ofindustrial automation equipment, and by the US Dept of Defense.andO;Successful implementation of concurrent design engineeringrequires a change in the architecture of the design environment,with the design process becoming integrated and supported fromproduct concept through manufacturing.andP;  Design knowledgeframeworks will be produced that will allow the extension of theautomation environment beyond the company to its vendors andcustomers, and will also allow design knowledge to be retained bythe company even when engineers leave.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Future of ComputingCircuit DesignAutomationTutorialEngineering.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>